The bar chart compares the weekly relative expenditures of families in one country in the years 1968 and 2018.

Across the 8 categories of goods and services, food was by far the dominant cost for a family in 1968, but which had greatly declined in importance by 2018. In contrast, leisure had seen the fastest growth in relative spending between 1968 and 2018.

Food used to be the indisputable number one cost for a family, accounting for 35% of its weekly income in 1968. This figure had almost halved by 2018. The same was true for clothing (including footwear) and personal goods: both had dropped to 5% and 4% respectively by 2018, half of their original percentages in 1968. Fuel and power also decreased in importance over the years, though not as dramatically, from 6% to 4%.

Among the categories that had seen a significant rise between the two years as a proportion of weekly spending, leisure had made the largest growth from 9% to 22%. A close second was housing, jumping from 10% to 19%. Transport also grew considerably from 8% to 14%, while household goods remained the same at 8% of weekly spending for both years.